{
  "text": "A serine/threonine kinase PDZ binding-kinase (PBK) is a member of the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) kinase (MAPKK) family [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This enzyme is also known under the name T-lymphokine-activated killer cell-originated protein kinase (TOPK). PBK was discovered as a factor that binds PDZ2 domain of hDLg (human homologue of the Drosophila Discs-large (Dlg) tumor suppressor protein) [CITATION_4] . This study also demonstrated that the mitotic phosphorylation of PBK is required for its kinase activity [CITATION_5] . Due to this specific activation during the mitotic-phase of the cell cycle, PBK is also denoted as a \"mitotic kinase\". PBK protein is phosphorylated by cdk1/ cyclin B during mitosis and its presence is necessary for formation of the mid-zone of the mitotic spindle [CITATION_6] . The PBK gene is especially highly expressed in placenta [CITATION_7] and was also implicated in spermatogenesis [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Since PBK is expressed in seminiferous tubules of testis, where the male gametes are produced, it has been speculated that PBK might be essential in spermatocytogenesis during which mitosis occurs [CITATION_10] . While PBK is not expressed in the adult human brain [CITATION_11] its mRNA is abundant in the human fetal brain [CITATION_12] and rapidly dividing neuronal stem/progenitor cells (NS/PCs) [CITATION_13] . In mouse NS/PCs both Pbk and its downstream target p38 are essential for proliferation and self-renewal [CITATION_14] . In the adult mouse brain, Pbk is expressed in rapidly proliferating NS/PCs of the adult subventricular zone and early postnatal cerebellar external granular layer [CITATION_15] . The notion that PBK represents a stemnessassociated kinase is further supported by the evidence that PBK is down regulated during differentiation [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] . PBK is specifically expressed in all germinal zones during brain development and is not expressed in mature neurons and glial cells [CITATION_18] . A study conducted in HL-60 myeloid leukemia cells, induced to differentiate, using phorbol ester, showed that PBK protein expression was strongly down-regulated in differentiated cells [CITATION_19] . This study also showed that the expression of PBK correlated positively with the expression of a cell cycle regulator c-Myc.",
